{{Infobox person |name = Frits Hansen |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1841|1|31|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Larvik]], Norway |death_date = {{Death date and age|1911|6|8|1841|1|31|df=y}} |death_place = |nationality = Norwegian |occupation = educator, newspaper editor, biographer and politician |known_for = |awards = }}
'''Frits Hansen''' (31 January 1841 – 8 June 1911) was a Norwegian educator, newspaper editor, biographer and politician.
Hansen was born at [[Larvik]], in [[Vestfold]], Norway. He was the son of Magistrate Frederik Christian Hansen (1799-1860) and Albine Elise Fougnerbakken (1801-1846). He earned his [[Cand.theol.]] degree in 1865. Subsequently, he became a teacher at the [[Norwegian Military Academy]]. From 1872, Hansen taught at [[Sagatun Folk High School]] in [[Hamar]]. In 1881 Hansen was a teacher at a private middle school in [[Stavanger]]. He was also editor of the [[Lillehammer]] newspaper ''Framgang''. In 1890, he wrote ''Edvard Storm, digteren fra Vaage'', a biography of the poet [[Edvard Storm]]. In 1896 he moved to [[Oslo|Christiania]] (now Oslo) and was editor of ''Eidsvold''.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Frits Hansen |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Arnfinn |last=Engen |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Frits_Hansen/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=3 August 2010}}</ref><ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Frits Hansen |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Frits_Hansen |language=Norwegian | accessdate=3 August 2010 }}</ref> He was the chairman and founder of the regional centrist-conservative political party [[Centre (political party)|Centre]] in the 1890s.<ref name=nbl/><ref name="NSD">[http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/data/parti/partihistorie/54 "Partihistorie: Centrum"]. ''Norsk samfunnsvitenskapelig datatjeneste''.</ref>
==Personal life== In 1872, he married Ingeborg Marie Heftye (1852-1894). Her father [[Thomas Johannessen Heftye]] was deputy representative to the [[Norwegian Parliament]] and her brother was Norwegian Defense Minister [[Thomas Heftye]]. Her grandfather [[Johannes Thomassen Heftye]] had founded the Norwegian bank company, [[Thos. Joh. Heftye & Søn]] . <ref>{{cite web|url= https://snl.no/Heftye|title= Heftye|publisher= Store norske leksikon|accessdate= July 1, 2016}}</ref>
